Background:

The data set consists of a sample of n=75 prisoners whose alcohol use was recorded. The following measures have been recorded:

  • alcohol: Alcohol Use Disorder Identification Test (AUDIT) score (it takes values from 0 to 18).
  • ethnic: Prisonerâs ethnicity (1=white, 2=black, 3=other)
  • offtype: Offense type (0=non-violent, 1=violent)
  • age: Age in years
  • sex: Gender (0=female, 1=male, 2=other)
  • sleep: How good the prisoner sleeps at night (1: good sleep, 2: so and so, 3: bad sleep)
  • communication: the extent to which the prisoner feels that has good communication with the prison psychologist (1: not at all â to 7: great communication).
  • Memoryloss: Measure of memory loss. Score taking values from 0 to 40.
  • Pure alcohol intake: Grams of pure alcohol intake per week in standard UBE units.
  • Pure alcohol intake parents: Grams of pure alcohol intake per week in standard UBE units by the subject parents.

Task 1

What kind of graph is the most appropriate to plot variable âPure alcohol intakeâ vs.Â âPure alcohol intake parentsâ?

A scatter plot is the most suitable graph to plot two continuous variables.

Is there a linear relationship between âPure alcohol intakeâ and âPure alcohol intake parentsâ? Use the plot from answer A to assess the linear relationship. Add a line of best fit to the plot, if necessary.

dataset %>% 
  
  ggplot(aes(x = purealcohol, 
             y = purealcohol_parents)) + 
    geom_point() + 
    geom_smooth(method = 'lm', formula = y~x) + 
    stat_cor() +  #ggpubr
    theme_bw() + 
    xlab('Pure alcohol intake (prisoner)') + 
    ylab('Pure alcohol intake (parents)') + 
    ggtitle('Relationship between prisoners and their parents\' alcohol intake')

Task 3

Build a simple linear model that can be used to predict the pure alcohol intake in prisoners knowing the pure alcohol intake in their parents. 
cor.test(x = dataset$purealcohol, 
         y = dataset$purealcohol_parents, 
         method = "pearson")
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  dataset$purealcohol and dataset$purealcohol_parents
## t = 6.2309, df = 73, p-value = 2.679e-08
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.4181881 0.7199119
## sample estimates:
##      cor 
## 0.589225

The Pearson correlation coefficient is 0.589. Based on this value, we can conclude there is a moderate positive linear relationship between the alcohol intake of the prisoners and the alcohol intake of the prisonersâ parents. We can infer this value to the whole population, as the p value is lower than 0.05 (p<0.001). This allows us to reject the null hypothesis of no linear correlation between the variables.

Task 3

          Î²_0=150.618     Î²_1= 0.522


Write the equation of the regression line.

purealcohol = 150.618 + 0.522 â purealcohol_parents

Interpret both regression coefficients.

150.618 UBE would be the extrapolated pure alcohol intake for a prisoner with parents that usually take no pure alcohol per week. 1 UBE difference in prisonersâ parentsâ alcohol intake is associated with a 0.522 UBE increase in prisonersâ alcohol intake.

Yes, we can infer the value to the whole population because the p-value for Î²1 in the statistical test (Task 3A output) is less than 0.05 (p<0.001). Therefore,we can reject the nullhypothesis ofð½ =0.

Task 5

A person is incarcerated. The team in the prison has information about his parentsâ pure alcohol intake per week, which is 210 UBE. They would like to know the prisonerâs pure alcohol weekly intake, but he rejects to answer the question. What would you recommend to the team? Can you use statistics to give a numerical estimation of the prisonerâs pure alcohol intake per week?

new.measure <- tibble(
  purealcohol_parents = c(210)
)

dataset %>% 
  lm(formula = purealcohol ~ purealcohol_parents) %>% 
  predict.lm(newdata = new.measure, 
             interval = "prediction")
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 260.3266 122.5127 398.1406

Task 7

What coefficient is the most appropriate to numerically assess the correlation between âalcoholâ and âmemorylossâ?

To be able to answer, first we need to check if both variables are normally distributed, following the next steps:

dataset %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = alcohol)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5)

dataset %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = memoryloss)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 2)

The variables are not normally distributed. Therefore, a Spearman correlation coefficient is more appropriate to measure the linear relationship between them.

Compute and interpret the correlation coefficient for the alcohol and memory loss variables. Can this value be inferred to the whole population?

cor.test(x = dataset$purealcohol, 
         y = dataset$purealcohol_parents, 
         method = "spearman")
## Warning in cor.test.default(x = dataset$purealcohol, y =
## dataset$purealcohol_parents, : Cannot compute exact p-value with ties
## 
##  Spearman's rank correlation rho
## 
## data:  dataset$purealcohol and dataset$purealcohol_parents
## S = 25665, p-value = 9.495e-10
## alternative hypothesis: true rho is not equal to 0
## sample estimates:
##       rho 
## 0.6349249

The Spearman correlation coefficient is 0.617. Based on this value, we can conclude there is a strong positive linear relationship between alcohol and memory loss. We can infer this value to the whole population, as the p value is less than 0.05 (p<0.001). This allows us to reject the null hypothesis of no linear correlation between the variables.
